@node Getting Started
@chapter Getting Started

In general a program in Dezyne consists of interfaces, components, and
``handwritten'' code, including a @code{main}.  For simple cases such as
the examples in this chapter, a generic @code{main} can be generated and
no handwritten code is needed.

The examples used in this chapter can be found in the Dezyne source tree
at @file{doc/examples/} or downloaded from
@url{https://savannah.nongnu.org/cgit/dezyne.git/dezyne/tree/doc/examples,
doc/examples/ in git}.

@menu
* Hello World!::                First contact with Dezyne.
* A Simple State Machine::      Stateful behavior and protocol.
* A Camera Example::            A System of Components and Systems.
* The Lego Ball Sorter::        A Machine Operating System.
@end menu

@node Hello World!
@section Hello World!

Consider the trivial Dezyne interface @code{ihello_world}

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/ihello-world.dzn
@end example

It defines two events, named @code{hello} and @code{world} of type
@code{void} and a trivial protocol in its @code{behavior}: whenever the
@code{hello} trigger is received (@code{on hello:}), it responds
synchronously with a @code{world} action.

This scenario can be explored using the simulator (@xref{Invoking dzn
simulate}):

@example
$ dzn simulate doc/examples/ihello-world.dzn
(header ((client) ihello_world provides) ((sut) ihello_world interface))
(state ((client)) ((sut)))
labels: hello
eligible: hello
>
@end example

As expected, @code{hello} is the only trigger that is eligible to
execute; entering @code{hello} gives

@example
> hello
<external>.hello -> ...
... -> sut.hello
... <- sut.world
<external>.world <- ...
... <- sut.return
<external>.return <- ...
(state ((client)) ((sut)))
(trail "hello" "world" "return")
labels: hello
eligible: hello
>
@end example

The simulator can also be run non-interactively to produce a friendlier
trace view or sequence diagram

@c generate automagically?
@c print less (state) ??
@c ./pre-inst-env dzn simulate --format=diagram doc/examples/ihello-world.dzn -t hello | tail +4 | head -11
@c XXX use ide diagram?
@example
client          ihello_world
  .                  :
  .                  :
  .hello             :
  .----------------->:
  .                  :
  .             world:
  .<-----------------:
  .                  :
  .            return:
  .<-----------------:
@end example

Now consider a trivial component @code{hello_world}

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/hello-world.dzn
@end example

it provides the @code{ihello_world} interface, which means that it
promises to behave according to the protocol specified in the interface.

The trigger @code{p.hello} is the event @code{hello} when communicated
over the port @code{p}, similarly the action is named @code{p.world}.
Simulation gives:

@example
$ dzn simulate --trail=p.hello doc/examples/hello-world.dzn
(header ((p) ihello_world provides) ((sut) hello_world component))
(state ((p)) ((sut)))
<external>.p.hello -> ...
... -> sut.p.hello
... <- sut.p.world
<external>.p.world <- ...
... <- sut.p.return
<external>.p.return <- ...
(state ((p)) ((sut)))
(trail "p.hello" "p.world" "p.return")
(state ((p)) ((sut)))
(labels "p.hello")
(eligible "p.hello")
@end example

with this trace diagram

@example
p          hello_world
.               :
.               :
.hello          :
.-------------->:
.               :
.          world:
.<--------------:
.               :
.         return:
.<--------------:
@end example

From this component an executable program can be created (@xref{Invoking dzn
code})
@example
$ dzn code doc/examples/ihello-world.dzn
$ dzn code --model=hello_world doc/examples/hello-world.dzn
$ g++ -I runtime/c++ hello-world.cc main.cc runtime/c++/runtime.cc runtime/c++/pump.cc -lpthread
@end example

When running this executable and feeding it the trail, we get
@example
echo 'p.hello p.world p.return' | ./a.out
<external>.p.hello -> sut.p.hello
<external>.p.world <- sut.p.world
<external>.p.return <- sut.p.return
@end example

@node A Simple State Machine
@section A Simple State Machine

The @code{ihello_bool} interface introduces stateful behavior that is
somewhat more interesting

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/ihello-bool.dzn
@end example

This example introduces some new language aspects

@table @code
@item bool idle = true;
A boolean state variable, defining @code{idle=true} as the initial
state,
@item [idle]
A @emph{guard}.  Only when the expression between the brackets evaluates
to @code{true} the @code{on} is eligible to execute.  In the initial
state, the @code{hello} trigger is the only thing that can occur.
The guard and the on are @emph{declarative} statements.  After the
declarative statements follows a,
@item idle = false;
An @emph{imperative} statement.  When @code{hello} trigger occurs, the
interface transitions to state @code{!idle},
@item on cruel: @dots{} on cruel: @dots{}
A non-deterministic choice@footnote{the caller does not resolve the choice
between the two cruel triggers, this is decided by the implementation}.
In the @code{!idle} state, @code{cruel} is accepted; it can either...
@item reply (true)
reply @code{false} and remain not idle, or
@item @{idle = true; reply (idle);@}
execute a compound of two imperative statements: Set the reply value to
@code{true} and transition to the idle state,
@item inevitable
If no @code{cruel} trigger occurs, @emph{inevitably} the @code{world}
action will occur.  @code{inevitable} is a @emph{modeling} event and is
not visible on the trail.  The effect is that @code{world} action now
has become @emph{decoupled} from the caller.
@end table

The state diagram (@xref{Invoking dzn graph}) depicts this protocol
graphically:

@image{images/ihello-bool,,,,.png}

This model is already interesting enough to have the mCRL2 model-checker
verify if all is well (@xref{Invoking dzn verify} and @xref{Verification
Checks and Errors})

@example
$ dzn -v verify doc/examples/ihello-bool.dzn
verify: ihello_bool: check: deadlock: ok
verify: ihello_bool: check: livelock: ok
verify: ihello_bool: check: deterministic: ok
@end example

which is luckily the case.  The model-checker can also be used to
generate all possible@footnote{the algorithm produces [traces that cover
every transition and every state} traces (@xref{Invoking dzn traces})
for @code{ihello_bool}:

@example
$ dzn -v traces doc/examples/ihello-bool.dzn
@end example

produces three trace files
(@file{ihello_bool.trace.0},@file{ihello_bool.trace.1}, and
@file{ihello_bool.trace.2}) with these traces (the order may differ):

@enumerate
@item
hello,return,world
@item
hello,return,cruel,true
@item
hello,return,cruel,false
@end enumerate

The sequence for the first trace with the asynchronous @code{world}
looks like this

@example
client          ihello_bool
  .                  :
  .                  :
  .hello             :
  .----------------->:
  .                  :
  .            return:
  .<-----------------:
  .                  :
  .                  :
  .             world:
  .<-----------------:
@end example

@noindent
and for the second trace where @code{cruel} happens looks like this

@example
client          ihello_bool
  .                  :
  .                  :
  .hello             :
  .----------------->:
  .                  :
  .            return:
  .<-----------------:
  .                  :
  .                  :
  .cruel             :
  .----------------->:
  .                  :
  .              true:
  .<-----------------:
@end example

@noindent
the third trace is looks like this

@example
client          ihello_bool
  .                  :
  .                  :
  .hello             :
  .----------------->:
  .                  :
  .            return:
  .<-----------------:
  .                  :
  .                  :
  .cruel             :
  .----------------->:
  .                  :
  .             false:
  .<-----------------:
@end example

@noindent
You may have noticed that the first two traces start and end in the
initial state, while the third trace starts in the initial state and
ends in the @code{!idle} state (also see the corresponding state
diagram).

Now have a look at the component @code{simple_state_machine}

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/simple-state-machine.dzn
@end example

It introduces the following concepts:
@table @code
@item enum status @{A, B, C@}
User defined @code{enum} type named @code{status},
@item [s.A]
Field test of enum variable @code{s}: evaluates to @code{true} if
@code{s} has field value @code{A}, it is equivalent to @code{s ==
status.A},
@item [s.B || s.C]
Logical or @code{||} in guard expression (see @xref{Expressions}),
@item on r2.world (): @{@}
A skip statement: upon receiving the @code{r2.world} trigger, the
component does ``nothing'' and is ready for the next event.  Omitting
this line would make the occurrence of @code{r2.world} @emph{illegal}.
@end table

@image{images/simple-state-machine,,,,.png}

Verification suceeds

@example
$ dzn -v verify doc/examples/simple-state-machine.dzn
verify: ihello_bool: check: deadlock: ok
verify: ihello_bool: check: livelock: ok
verify: ihello_bool: check: deterministic: ok
verify: iworld: check: deadlock: ok
verify: iworld: check: livelock: ok
verify: iworld: check: deterministic: ok
verify: simple_state_machine: check: deterministic: ok
verify: simple_state_machine: check: illegal: ok
verify: simple_state_machine: check: deadlock: ok
verify: simple_state_machine: check: livelock: ok
verify: simple_state_machine: check: compliance: ok
@end example

you may want to see what happens to verification or the state diagram
when you comment-out a statement of your choosing in the component's
behavior.

@node A Camera Example
@section A Camera Example

The @code{Camera} example introduces the system component
(@xref{Systems}).  The system diagram (@xref{Invoking dzn graph}) looks
like this:

@image{images/Camera-system,,,,.png}

This is what the Camera system looks like in Dezyne:
@example
component Camera
@{
  provides IControl control;

  system
  @{
    Driver driver;
    Acquisition acquisition;
    Optics optics;

    control <=> driver.control;
    driver.acquisition <=> acquisition.port;
    driver.optics <=> optics.port;
  @}
@}
@end example

It introduces the following concepts:
@table @code
@item provides IControl control;
Similar to a regular component, it defines ports,
@item system
The @code{system} specification defines @emph{instances} of components
and their @emph{bindings},
@item Driver driver;
A component instance named @code{driver} of type @code{Driver},
@item Acquisition acquisition;
A component instance named @code{acquisition} of type @code{Acquisition},
which is a @code{system} component itself,
@item Optics optics;
An instance of another @code{system} component,
@item control <=> driver.control;
A binding of the @code{Camera}'s port @code{control} to the port named
@code{control} of the @code{driver} instance.
@item driver.acquisition <=> acquisition.port;
A binding between pairs of ports on component instances.
@end table

The light blue components in the system view, such as @code{lens} are
@emph{foreign} components (@xref{Components}); their definition
looks like this:

@example
component Lens
@{
  provides ILens port;
@}
@end example

A foreign component does not specify any implementation: neither a
@code{behavior} nor a @code{system}; its behavior is said to be
implementation elsewhere, and in a foreign language (in this case
@code{C++}).

The full example is contained in the source tree at
@file{test/all/Camera/Camera.dzn} or
@url{https://savannah.nongnu.org/cgit/dezyne.git/dezyne/tree/test/all/Camera/Camera.dzn,
Camera.dzn}.

The simplified@footnote{A simplified state diagram shows only triggers
on state transitions and hides any actions or reply values.  Also, the
state of the ports or even all extended state can be removed.  For this
diagram, the command @code{dzn graph --backend=state --hide=actions
--remove=extended test/all/Camera/Camera.dzn} was used.} state diagram:

