@node Invoking dzn
@section Invoking @command{dzn}

The @command{dzn} command is a front-end to Dezyne functions.

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} @code{command} @var{command-option}@dots{} @file{FILE}...
@end example

Invoking @code{dzn} without @code{command} shows a list of available
commands.

The @var{dzn-option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --debug
@itemx -d
Enable debug ouput.

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @code{dzn}, and then exit.

@c XXX move to structured output, recutils?
@item --json
@itemx -j
For internal use: output data as JSON.

@item --skip-wfc
@itemx -p
Use plain @var{peg} parser, skip Well-formedness
(@xref{Well-formedness}) checking.

@item --verbose
@itemx -v
Be more verbose, show progress.

@item --version
@itemx -V
Display the current version of @code{dzn}, and then exit.

@end table

Running @code{dzn} without @var{command} shows a list of available dzn
commands:

@example
Usage: dzn [OPTION]... COMMAND [COMMAND-ARGUMENT...]
  -d, --debug            enable debug ouput
  -h, --help             display this help
  -j, --json             output json
  -p, --skip-wfc         use plain PEG, skip well-formedness checking
  -v, --verbose          be more verbose, show progress
  -V, --version          display version

Commands:
  code
  explore
  hello
  language
  lts
  parse
  simulate
  trace
  traces
  verify

Use "dzn COMMAND --help" for command-specific information.
@end example

@node Invoking dzn code
@section Invoking @command{dzn code}

The @command{dzn code} command generates C++ code for a Dezyne model
file.  @xref{Code Integration}.

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} code @var{option}@dots{} @file{FILE}
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --calling-context=@var{type}
@itemx -c @var{type}
Generate extra parameter of @var{type} for every event.

@item --glue=@var{type}
@itemx -g @var{type}
Generate glue for @var{type} var.

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @code{dzn code}, and then exit.

@item --import=@var{dir}
@itemx -I @var{dir}
Add directory @var{dir} to the import path.

@item --init=@var{PROCESS}
When generating @code{mCRL2} code, use init @var{PROCESS}.

@item --language=@var{language}
@itemx -l @var{language}
Generate code for language @var{language} var.

@item --model=@var{model}
@itemx -m @var{model}
Generate main for @var{model}.

@item --output=@var{dir}
@itemx -o @var{dir}
Write output to directory @var{dir} (use @code{-} for stadard output).

@item --queue-size=@var{size}
@itemx -q @var{size}
Use queue size @var{size} for verification, the default is @code{3}.

@item --shell=@var{model}
@itemx -s @var{model}
Generate thread-safe system shell for model @var{model}.
@xref{Thread-safe Shell}.

@end table

@node Invoking dzn explore
@section Invoking @command{dzn explore}

@quotation Note
explore is deprecated, please use graph @xref{Invoking dzn graph}.
@end quotation

@cindex Aldebaran
@cindex @code{lts}

The @command{dzn explore} command generates a state diagram or an
@code{lts} for a Dezyne model (@xref{Invoking dzn lts}, @xref{Invoking
dzn traces}).

Under the hood, @command{dzn explore} uses the Dezyne VM.

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} explore @var{option}@dots{} @file{FILE}
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @code{dzn explore}, and then exit.

@item --import=@var{dir}
@itemx -I @var{dir}
Add directory @var{dir} to the import path.

@item --lts
Generate an @code{lts} in Aldebaren format.

@item --model=@var{model}
@itemx -m @var{model}
Explore model @var{model}.  The default is to use the most
``interesting'' model.

@item --queue-size=@var{size}
@itemx -q @var{size}
Use queue size @var{size} for exploration, the default is @code{3}.

@item --state-diagram
Generate a state-diagram it @code{dot} format.  This is the default.

@end table


@node Invoking dzn graph
@section Invoking @command{dzn graph}

The @command{dzn graph} command generates a graph from a Dezyne model.

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} graph @var{option}@dots{} @file{FILE}
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --backend=@var{type}
@itemx -b @var{type}
Generate a diagram using backend @var{type}; one of @code{dependency},
@code{lts}, @code{state}, or @code{system} and write it to standard
output.  The default is @code{system}.

The @code{state} diagram can simplified using options @option{--hide}
and @option{remove}.

@cindex Aldebaran
@cindex @code{lts}
Under the hood, @code{lts} and @code{state} use the Dezyne VM.  See also
@ref{Invoking dzn lts}, and @ref{Invoking dzn traces}).

@item --format=@var{format}
@itemx -f @var{format}
Print trace in format @var{format}; one of @code{aut}, @code{dot}, or
n@code{json}.  For @option{--lts} the default is @code{aut}, for other
formats the default is @code{dot}.

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @code{dzn graph}, and then exit.

@item --hide=@var{hide}
@itemx -H @var{hide}
Generate a state diagram and hide @var{hide} from the transitions; one
of @code{labels} (hide everything) or @code{actions}.

@item --import=@var{dir}
@itemx -I @var{dir}
Add directory @var{dir} to the import path.

@item --model=@var{model}
@itemx -m @var{model}
Generate graph for model @var{model}.  The default is to use the most
``interesting'' model.

@item --queue-size=@var{size}
@itemx -q @var{size}
Use queue size @var{size} for exploration, the default is @code{3}.

@item --remove=@var{vars}
@itemx -R @var{vars}
Generate a state diagram and remove variables from nodes @var{remove};
one of @code{ports} or @code{extended}.

@code{ports} Hides the state of the component's or system's ports,
@code{extended} hides the interface's or component's extended state,
i.e., all but the main (first) state variable and implies @code{ports}.

@end table


