Under the hood, @command{dzn traces} uses @command{dzn code} and mCRL2.

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} traces @var{option}@dots{} @file{FILE}
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --flush
@itemx -f
Include @code{<flush>} events in trace.

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @code{dzn traces}, and then exit.

@item --illegal
@itemx -i
Include traces that lead to an illegal.

@item --import=@var{dir}
@itemx -I @var{dir}
Add directory @var{dir} to the import path.

@item --lts
@itemx -l
Instead of generating trace files, generate an @var{lts} in Aldebaran
format.

@item --model=@var{model}
@itemx -m @var{model}
Generate traces for model @var{model}.

@item --output=@var{dir}
@itemx -o @var{dir}
Write trace files to directory @var{dir}.

@item --queue-size=@var{size}
@itemx -q @var{size}
Use queue size @var{size} for generation, the default is @code{3}.

@item --traces
@itemx -t
Generate trace files, this is the default.  Using @option{--traces} will
