@end table

@node Invoking dzn verify
@section Invoking @command{dzn verify}

The @command{dzn verify} command checks a Dezyne file for verification
errors in Dezyne models.  @xref{Formal Verification}.

@example
dzn @var{dzn-option}@dots{} verify @var{option}@dots{} @file{FILE}
@end example

The @var{option}s can be among the following:

@table @code

@item --all
@itemx -a
Show all errors, i.e., keep going after finding an error.  By default,
verification stops after finding a verification error.

@item --help
@itemx -h
Display help on invoking @code{dzn verify}, and then exit.

@item --import=@var{dir}
@itemx -I @var{dir}
Add directory @var{dir} to the import path.

@item --model=@var{model}
@itemx -m @var{model}
Limit verification to @var{model}, and for a behavioral component
model, to its interfaces.

@quotation Note
Verification cannot be limited to @code{system} component models;
verifying a system model is a no-op@footnote{The compositional property
of the Dezyne component-based programming paradigm guarantees that the
verification of a @code{system} component model amounts to the
verification of all its @code{interface} models and behavioral
@code{component} models.}.
@c XXX TODO: reference to compositional quality/property
@end quotation

@item --no-interface-determinism
Do not run the observable non-determinism check on interfaces.

@item --out=@var{format}
Run a partial verification pipeline to produce @var{format}.
Interesting formats are @code{mcrl2}, @code{aut},
@code{aut-dpweak-bisim}, @code{aut-weak-trace}, and
@code{aut+provides-aut}.  Use @option{--out=help} for a full list.

Using the @option{--debug} on @command{dzn} (@xref{Invoking dzn}) shows
the pipelines with all their commands that are being used, ready for
use on the command line.

@item --queue-size=@var{size}
@itemx -q @var{size}
Use queue size @var{size} for verification, the default is @code{3}.

@end table

@node Dezyne Language Reference
@chapter Dezyne Language Reference

Dezyne is a component based language as well as a method for the
development of event-driven systems.  The language has formal semantics,
which is coherently expressed in: a textual representation, a graphical
representation, a mathematical representation, a source code
representation, and the observable behavior of a machine executing the
resulting program.  The concepts available in the language denote the
different properties@footnote{ Structural: events and their direction in
an interface, ports on a component, components in a system, bindings
between the ports; behavioral: guarded triggers performing actions |
assignments | if-else | functions} that can be observed and have meaning
in one or more of the representations: textual, graphical, mathematical,
program and execution.

The @code{C}-like syntax of Dezyne should give it a familiar feel to
many programmers.  Dezyne has some unique language concepts and syntax
elements that are described in this chapter.

@menu
* Lexical Analysis::            Tokens, separators and whitespace.
* Dezyne Files::                What goes into a Dezyne file?
* Types and Expressions::       Manipulating data in Dezyne.
* Interfaces::                  Defining contracts for components and systems.
* Components::                  Defining a program's behavior in Dezyne.
* Systems::                     Decomposing a system.
* Namespaces::                  Avoiding name collision.
@end menu

@node Lexical Analysis
@section Lexical Analysis

@cindex parser
@cindex parsing
@cindex PEG
Dezyne is a @code{C}-like language.  This means that identifiers must be
separated by either whitespace, delimiters or operators and is otherwise
whitespace invariant.  The Dezyne parser is defined using a partial
expression grammar or ``PEG'' (@pxref{PEG Parsing,,, guile, GNU Guile
Reference Manual}).

@menu
* Identifiers::                 Choosing names.
* Keywords::                    Restricted words.
* Operators::                   Building blocks for expressions.
* Delimiters::                  Constructing lists.
* Lexical Scoping::             Locality of names.
* Comments::                    Explanations for human readers.
@end menu

@node Identifiers
@subsection Identifiers

In Dezyne identifiers are used to name objects like interfaces,
components, events, user defined types, variables, etc.  A keyword
cannot be used as an identifier and identifiers are case-sensitive.

@example
identifier ::= [a-zA-Z_][a-zA-Z0-9_]*
@end example

An identifier starts with a letter or an underscore, which can be
followed by further letters, digits, or underscores.  The following are
all valid identifiers:

@example
p, hello, Alarm, turn_on, VALUE_123, _
@end example

@quotation Note
That by convention Dezyne identifiers are also used in the target
language, however the target language may impose further restrictions on
identifiers.
@end quotation

@node Keywords
@subsection Keywords

The following list shows identifiers that are reserved words in Dezyne,
or @emph{keywords}.  These keywords may not be used as an identifier
name.

@example
behavior        blocking        bool            component
else            extern          external        enum
false           if              illegal         import
inevitable      injected        inout           interface
in              namespace       on              optional
otherwise       out             provides        reply
requires        return          subint          system
true
@end example

@node Operators
@subsection Operators

Dezyne uses infix notation for expressions.  The following are operators
in Dezyne:
@example
+       -       !
<       >       <=      >=      ==      !=      <=>
@end example

@node Delimiters
@subsection Delimiters

The following are delimiters in Dezyne, for introducing lists:

@example
(       )       @{       @}       $
@end example

and for elements in lists:

@example
,       .       ;       =
@end example

@node Lexical Scoping
@subsection Lexical Scoping

A lexical @emph{scope} adds locality to a name.  Names in one lexical
scope do not interfere (collide or shadow) with another scope.
Referring to a scoped identifier

@example
  reference :: scope* identifier
  scope :: identifier "."
@end example

Dezyne defines the following scopes:

@table @code
@item enum
The field values of an enum:

@example
enum result @{TRUE, FALSE, ERROR@};
@end example

are referenced to by using the enum type name as scope:

@example
result.TRUE
@end example

@item interface
A type defined in an interface:

@example
interface ihello
@{
   enum result @{TRUE, FALSE, ERROR@};
@}
@end example

can be used in a component, e.g., to define a variable:

@example
ihello.result status = ihello.result.TRUE;
@end example

@item behavior
All definitions in a behavior are local to that behavior and cannot be
referenced from outside it@footnote{This may change when Dezyne gains
support for hierarchical behaviors, a.k.a. submachines.},

@item port
A port is an interface instance; events that are communicated over a
port use the name of the port as their scope:

@example
provides ihello p;
@dots{}
on p.hello (): p.world ();
@end example

@item instance
An @code{instance} (or component instance), is an instance of a
component.  A port defined in a component

@example
component hello
@{
  provides ihello p;
  requires ihello r;
@}

@end example

can be referenced to by using the component instance name as their scope

@example
component sys
@{
  provides ihello sp;
  requires ihello sr;
  system
  @{
    hello h;
    sp <=> h.p;
    h.r <=> sr;
  @}
@}
@end example

@item namespace
Types defined in a namespace are referenced to by using the name of the
namespace as their scope.
@c TODO add example
@end table

@node Comments
@subsection Comments

Dezyne supports single-line and multi-line comments very similar to
@code{C}.  Multi-line comments may be nested.  All characters part of a
comment are skipped by the parser.

@example
/* This is an example of multi-line comment.
 * The line below is ignored also:
 * this component implements...
 */
component hello
@{
  provides ihello p; // a single-line comment
@}
@end example

@node Dezyne Files
@section Dezyne Files

Dezyne types, interfaces, and components are organized in files.  A
file, with extension '.dzn' by convention, may contain zero or more of
type definitions, interfaces, and/or components.

The toplevel Dezyne program text is defined as follows:

@example
text ::= root
root ::= (import | data-expression
           | namespace | type | interface | component)*
@end example

An interface can refer to a global type definition.  A component can
refer to types, interfaces and other components.  An explicit
@code{import} clause is needed when the referred information is defined
in another file.

@subsection Import

@cindex file import
@cindex import
An @code{import} clause makes available all types, interfaces and
components that are defined in another file.  From an imported interface
or component the 'public' parts are available, i.e., all information but
the interface or component behavior, or the component system details.

@example
import    ::= "import" (file-name "/")* file-name ";"
file-name ::= [a-zA-Z0-9_+.-]+
@end example

@quotation Note
That by convention the basename of the Dezyne file-name is used as the
target language basename, however the target platform may impose further
restrictions on a file-name.
@end quotation

By convention, Dezyne files use the extension @code{.dzn}.  Some
examples:

@example
import file-name.dzn;
import ../global-types.dzn;
import some/directory/prefix/library.dzn;
@end example

An imported file may contain imports itself, these are also imported.
When a file occurs twice in the resulting set of imports, it is expanded
only once.  This avoids introducing duplicate definitions.  Mutually
recursive imports are allowed (@xref{Invoking dzn parse}).

@node Types and Expressions
@section Types and Expressions

In Dezyne all variables and constants are typed.  A number of type
constructs are available.

@example
type      ::= bool / enum / subint / void
data-type ::= extern
@end example

@code{type}s are used for event reply types, variables,
function parameters, function, function return types, and function call
arguments.  @code{data-types} are used for event parameters, action
arguments, and variables.

@menu
* Void::                        Definitions without type.
* Bool::                        Builtin boolean type.
* Enum::                        Enumerated user types.
* Subint::                      Integer user types.
* Extern Data Type::            Foreign data user types.
* Expressions::                 Constants and data.
@end menu

@node Void
@subsection @code{void}

@code{void} is used for defining untyped events and functions, e.g.,

an event without reply value:

@example
in void hello ();
@end example

a function without return value:

@example
void foo ()
@{
  world;
@}
@end example

@node Bool
@subsection @code{bool}

@cindex bool type
@cindex true
@cindex false
Dezyne has a builtin boolean type @code{bool} with constants
@code{false} and @code{true}.

Available boolean operators are:

@table @code
@item !b
Logical negation of a boolean expression,
@item b1 && b2
Logical and of two boolean expressions,
@item b1 || b2
Logical or of two boolean expressions,
@item b1 == b2
Equality of two boolean expressions,
@item b1 != b2
Inequality of two boolean expressions,
@end table
where @code{b}, @code{b1}, and @code{b2} are boolean expressions.

It is used to define boolean events

@example
in bool test ();
@end example

boolean variables

@example
bool idle = true;
@end example

and parameters and functions

@example
bool negate (bool input)
@{
  return !input;
@}
@end example

@node Enum
@subsection @code{enum}

@cindex enum type
An interface or component can specify a user defined enumerated
type.  Such a type has a name and a list of values.

@example
enum   ::= "enum" identifier "@{" fields "@}" ";"
fields ::= identifier ("," identifier)* ","?
@end example

An example:

@example
enum result @{FALSE,TRUE,ERROR@};
@end example

where @code{enum} is a keyword; this defines the enum type @code{result}
with three values.

In expressions the enum values are referred to with a dot notation:
@code{result.FALSE}.

Available enum operators are:

@table @code
@item e1 == e2
Equality of two enum expressions,
@item e1 != e2
Inequality of two enum expressions,
@item v.ERROR
A field-test: testing the value of an enum variable, denoted by
@code{v.ERROR}, which is shorthand for @code{v == result.ERROR}
@end table
where @code{e1} and @code{e2} denote enum expressions, and @code{v} an
enum variable of type @code{result}.

@node Subint
@subsection @code{subint}

@cindex integer type
@cindex subint type
The integer type is available in Dezyne in a restricted way@footnote{the
subint definition allows range checking and prevents accidental
unboundedness during model checking}: only a finite contiguous subrange
of integer numbers can be used.  An explicit type definition is needed
for each subset, where a @code{C}-like syntax is used.

@example
subint  ::= "subint" identifier "@{" range "@}" ";"
range   ::= integer ".." integer
integer ::= ("-")? [0-9]+
@end example

An example:

@example
subint int @{-1..2@};
@end example

where @code{subint} is a keyword.  This defines the finite type
@code{int} with possible values -1, 0, 1, and 2.  Available integer
operators are:

@table @code

@item comparison

@table @code
@item i1
@item i1 <= i2
@item i1 >= i2
@item i1 >  i2
@item i1 == i2
@item i1 != i2
@end table

@item i1 + i2,
Integer addition,
@item i1 - i2
Integer subtraction,
@end table
where @code{i1} and @code{i2} denote integers.

@quotation note
Integers of different @code{subint} types can be used in comparison,
assignment, and function calls.  The verifier will check that the
resulting integer value is within the defined @code{subint} range.
@end quotation

@node Extern Data Type
@subsection @code{extern} data

@cindex data type
@cindex extern
Apart from @code{bool}, @code{enum}, and @code{int} types introduced
above, also @code{extern} data types can be defined.  An @code{extern}
data type is defined as follows:

@cindex data-expression
@example
extern          ::= "extern" identifier data-expression ";"
data-expression ::= "$" (!"$")* "$"
@end example

The @code{data-expression} is a type expression in the target
language.

No Dezyne-supported expressions are available for data types, apart from
@code{data-expression}s.  The content of the data-expression is passed
to the target language verbatim.

For example, a @code{C++} string type could be defined as follows:

@example
extern string $std::string$;
@end example

@node Expressions
@subsection Expressions

Expressions in Dezyne are strictly typed.

@cindex bool-expression
@cindex boolean-expression
@example
expression ::= bool-expression | data-expression | enum-expression
                | integer-expression
@end example

@quotation Note
The well-formedness check (@xref{Well-formedness}) verifies that
expressions are of the correct type.
@end quotation

@subsubheading Bool Expressions

@example
bool-expression ::= bool-literal
                     | action
                     | call
                     | field-test
                     | "!" bool-expression
                     | "(" bool-expression ")"
                     | bool-expression bool-operator bool-expression
                     | int-expression comparison-operator int-expression
bool-literal    ::= "false" | "true"
field-test      ::= enum-variable "." enum-field
bool-operator   ::= "==" | "!=" | "&&" | "||"
comparison-operator
                ::= "==" | "!=" | "<" | "<=" | ">" | ">="
@end example

where @code{action} and @code{call} are of type @code{bool}.

@subsubheading Enum Expressions

@cindex enum-expression
@example
enum-expression ::= enum-literal
                     | action
                     | call
enum-literal    ::= enum "." field
@end example

where @code{action} and @code{call} are of the correct @code{enum} type.

@subsubheading Int Expressions

@cindex int-expression
@cindex integer-expression
@example
int-expression ::= int-literal
                     | action
                     | call
                     | int-expression int-operator int-expression
int-literal    ::= "-"? [0-9]+
int-operator   ::= "+" | "-"
@end example

where @code{action} and @code{call} are of a @code{subint} type.

@node Interfaces
@section Interfaces

@cindex event
@cindex interface
@cindex message
Interfaces describe the interaction between two components: the events
(or messages) that can and cannot be communicated, i.e., the interaction
protocol.

@example
interface ::= "interface" identifier "@{" types-and-events behavior "@}"
type-and-events
          ::= (type | event)*
behavior  ::= "behavior" "@{" behavior-statement* "@}"
@end example

Each event has a direction specified by the @code{in} or @code{out}
keywords.  An event labeled with @code{in} (@code{in}-event) is received
by the implementation providing the interface.  Conversely, an event
labeled with @code{out} (@code{out}-event) is emitted by the
implementation providing the interface.  Note that from the point of
view of an implementation requiring an interface the interpretation of
@code{in} and @code{out} is inverted.

The interface protocol is specified in the @code{behavior} section.

@example
$include <string>;$
interface ihello
@{
  @b{enum} result @{FALSE,TRUE,ERROR@};
  @b{extern} string $std::string$;
  @b{in} result hello (string greeting);
  @b{out} void world ();
  @b{behavior} @{ @dots{} @}
@}
@end example

@menu
* Events::                      Event or message definitions.
* Behavior::                    Specifying an interface protocol.
* Declarative Statements::      Define when to run which trigger.
* Imperative Statements::       The code that runs upon a trigger.
* Functions::                   Avoiding code duplication.
@end menu

@node Events
@subsection Events

Events are messages or function calls and returns that are communicated
between components.

@example
event     ::= direction type identifier "(" parameter-list? ")" ";"
direction ::= "in" | "out"
parameter-list
          ::= parameter ( "," parameter)*
parameter ::= parameter-direction? data-type identifier
parameter-direction
          ::= "in" | "out" | "inout"
@end example

Some examples.

A void in-event called @code{e} with an empty parameter list:

@example
in void e ();
@end example

a valued in-event called @code{e2}:

@example
in enum_type e2 ();
@end example

a void in-event called @code{e3} with two data parameters

@example
out void e3 (some_id in_id, out some_id out_id);
@end example

a void out-event called @code{e4} with a data parameter

@example
out void e4 (some_string s);
@end example

@quotation Note
There are two restrictions on @code{out}-event definitions:
@itemize
@item
@code{out}-events must be of type @code{void}, and
@item
@code{out}-events can only take @code{in} parameters.
@end itemize
@end quotation

@subsubsection Modeling Events

Apart from user-defined events, Dezyne has two special builtin events
called @code{optional} and @code{inevitable}.  These are called
``modeling events'' and are used in interface to specify
@emph{decoupled} behavior (@xref{Using inevitable and optional}).

@node Behavior
@subsection Behavior

The @code{behavior} section of an interface defines the protocol of the
interface.  The protocol prescribes the causal relation between events
and state.  The behavior is akin to a state machine.

@example
behavior           ::= "behavior" "@{" behavior-statement* "@}"
behavior-statement ::= type | variable | function | declarative-statement
@end example

@menu
* Behavior Variable::           The detailed state of the behavior.
@end menu

@node Behavior Variable
@subsubsection Behavior @code{variable}

The @code{behavior} variables define the state of the behavior.
They are sometime referred to as @emph{state variables}.

@example
variable ::= (type identifier = expression
                | data-type identifier = data-expression
                | data-type identifier) ";"
@end example

where @code{type} and @code{expression} must match.

For example:

@example
bool idle = true;
@end example

@quotation Note
The @code{expression} used in the definition of a behavior variable must
be a constant expression, i.e.: no @code{action}, @code{call} or
@code{variable}-reference is allowed.
@end quotation

@node Declarative Statements
@subsection Declarative Statements

A trigger is prescribed by an interface to be handled by an
implementation as is the condition under which it occurs.  Collectively
this is referred to as a declarative statement.  The condition is
expressed as a @code{guard}, the trigger in an @code{on}.  The code that
is executed when both the guard expression evaluates to @code{true} and
the trigger occurs, is called the @emph{imperative statement}
(@xref{Imperative Statements}).

@example
declarative-statement ::= guard | on | "@{" declarative-statement "@}"
@end example

The combination of all declarative statements leading up to a
@code{imperative statement} is also called the declarative
@emph{prefix}.  The combination of all @code{guard}s, the @code{on} and
the @code{imperative statement} is sometimes referred to as a
@emph{transition}.

@example
transition   ::= prefix imperative-statement
prefix       ::= <guards> <on>
@end example

@menu
* On::                          Defining what happens upon a trigger.
* Guard::                       Declarative trigger condition.
* Using inevitable and optional::  Nitty gritty details on using modeling events.
@end menu

@node On
@subsubsection @code{on}

The @code{on} defines which trigger is to be handled:

@example
on        ::= "on" trigger ("," trigger)* ":" statement
trigger   ::= event-name | "inevitable" | "optional"
statement ::= declarative-statement | imperative-statement | illegal
imperative-statement
          ::= action | assign | call | if | reply | return | variable
                | imperative-compound
                | empty-statement
illegal   ::= "illegal"
imperative-compound
          ::= "@{" (imperative-statement ";")+ "@}"
empty-statement
          ::= ";" | "@{" "@}"
@end example

For example:

@example
on hello: @{@}
on inevitable: @{world; idle = true;@}
@end example

When two or more observably distinct imperative statements are specified
for a certain trigger, the interface is said to behave
@emph{non-deterministic} with respect to the trigger.  For example:

@example
on hello: world;
on hello: cruel;
@end example

when the trigger @code{hello} is sent, the response can either be
@code{world} or @code{cruel} but which one it will be cannot be
predicted.  Non-determinism in interfaces is allowed as long as it is
@emph{observable non-determinism}, i.e., after the trigger has returned
the client should be able to know which state the interface is in.  For
example, this is not allowed:

@example
on hello: @{@}
on hello: idle = true;
@end example

and will lead to a verification error (@xref{Verification Checks and
Errors}).

@quotation Note

@itemize
@item
There must be exactly one imperative statement for every combination of
@code{guard} and @code{on},
@item
There can be only one @code{on} leading to an imperative statement.
@end itemize
@end quotation

@node Guard
@subsubsection @code{guard}

@example
guard ::= "[" bool-expression "]" statement
@end example

For example:

@example
[idle]  on hello: idle = false;
[!idle]
@{
  on hello: idle = true;
  on inevitable: @{world; idle = true;@}
@}
@end example

@node Using inevitable and optional
@subsubsection Using @code{inevitable} and @code{optional}

In interfaces, two @emph{modeling} events may be used as abstract
triggers, i.e.@: @code{inevitable} and @code{optional}:

@example
on inevitable: imperative-statement;
on optional:   imperative-statement;
@end example

Where @code{inevitable} implies that if no other triggers occur, this
trigger is guaranteed to occur, and @code{optional} implies that the
trigger may or may never occur.

Note that an inevitable event is not allways guaranteed to occur, it is
only inevitable in the absence of other events.

An example of an interface using both inevitable and optional.

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/inevitable-optional.dzn
@end example

In the interface above a reply value of @code{true} on @code{hello}
informs the client sending the @code{hello} that the @code{world} can be
waited on.  However in case the reply value of @code{hello} is
@code{false} and the client would sit there waiting for @code{cruel} to
happen, they may sit there forever because @code{cruel} might never
happen.  This is what we refer to as a @emph{deadlock}.  To avoid this
@emph{deadlock} as a client, they must make sure that they can handle a
@code{cruel} in case it does happen and that they have another way of
making progress in case @code{cruel} never happens.

Conversely, the implementation of this interface may choose to perform
the cruel always, never or intermittently after a @code{hello} followed
by a @code{false}, but it must (being contractually required) always do
a @code{world} after a @code{hello} followed by a @code{true}.

@node Imperative Statements
@subsection Imperative Statements

The imperative statement is the statement that will be executed when a
guarded trigger occurs (see also @xref{Declarative Statements}).

@menu
* Action::                      Emitting events.
* Assign::                      Updating state.
* Function Call::               A named collection of imperative statements.
* Empty Statement::             When a trigger has no effect, or there is nothing to do.
* If::                          Imperative decisions.
* Illegal::                     Specifying what is not allowed.
* Reply::                       Determining the reply for a valued trigger.
* Return::                      Returning from a function.
* Variable::                    Defining a local variable.
@end menu

@node Action
@subsubsection @code{action}

When handling a trigger (a @code{in}-event), an interface can emit zero
or more @code{out}-events.  The event that follows a trigger is are
referred to as an @code{action}.

@example
action ::= event-name ";"
@end example

where @code{event-name} is the name of an @code{out}-event defined in
the interface.

For example

@example
world;
@end example

@node Assign
@subsubsection @code{assign}

The value of a previously defined variable can be updated using an
@code{assign}:

@example
assign ::= variable "=" expression ";"
@end example

For example:

@example
idle = true;
idle = !b;
idle = negate (idle);
@end example

where @code{b} and @code{idle} are variables of type @code{bool},
@code{negate} is a function with one @code{bool} parameter and
return-type @code{bool} (see @xref{Function Call}).

@node Function Call
@subsubsection @code{call}

@example
call          ::= identifier "(" argument-list ")"
argument-list ::= (expression ",")*
@end example

For example:

@example
foo ();
bar (true, 12);
@end example

Note that the value returned by a @code{call} to a non-@code{void}
@code{function} is not allowed to be ignored.  Therefore in the example
above both @code{foo} and @code{bar} must be @code{function}s of type
@code{void}.  By capturing the value in a variable definition or the use
of an @code{assign} to an existing variable is the proper way to handle
the return value:

@example
bool b = bool_function ();
b = bool_function ();
@end example

Another way is to properly use a return value is in simple expressions,
possibly combined with: @b{==}, @b{!=}, @b{!}, @b{&&}, @b{||} (since
2.14.0)

@example
if (bool_function ()) @dots{};
if (!bool_function ()) @dots{};
if (!bool_function () && b) @dots{};
if (enum_function () == result.FALSE) @dots{};
if (enum_function () != result.TRUE || b) @dots{};
reply (enum_function ());
reply (enum_function () != result.ERROR);
@end example

@node Empty Statement
@subsubsection Empty Statement

@cindex empty statement
@cindex skip
The empty statement or @code{skip} statement defines for @emph{nothing}
to happen.

@example
empty-statement ::=  ";" | "@{" "@}"
@end example

For example:

@example
on hello: @{@}
on cruel: ;
@end example

@node If
@subsubsection @code{if}

Conditional handling of statements is supported by the @code{if}, which
can have an optional else:

@example
if ::= ("if" "(" bool-expression ")" imperative-statement)
         | ("if" "(" bool-expression ")" imperative-statement
              "else" imperative-statement)
@end example

For example

@example
if (idle)
  @{world; idle = false;@}
else
  cruel;
@end example

Since 2.14.0, a valued @code{call} may be used in an
@code{if}-expression.

For example:

@example
if (bool_function ()) @dots{};
if (!bool_function ()) @dots{};
if (!bool_function () && b) @dots{};
if (enum_function () == result.TRUE) @dots{};
if (enum_function () != result.ERROR || b) @dots{};
@end example

Note that nested @code{if}s are allowed:

@example
if (b1) if (b2) then-statement else else-statement
@end example

is interpreted as

@example
if (b1)
@{ if (b2) then-statement else else-statement @}
@end example

In other words: @code{else} binds to the closest @code{if}.

@quotation Note
In an interface, an @code{illegal} is not allowed as a then-statement or
an else-statement, however the same can be expressed using a
@code{guard}.
@end quotation

@node Illegal
@subsubsection @code{illegal}

A trigger can be explicitly marked as being @code{illegal} in a certain
state.  In that case, @code{illegal} must be the only imperative
statement for that trigger.

@example
illegal ::= "illegal" ";"
@end example

For example:

@example
on hello: illegal;
@end example

@quotation Note
Since 2.14.0, a declarative-statement followed by an @code{illegal} can
be completely omitted, since it has the same meaning.  It is however
still available for backwards compatibility.
@end quotation

@node Reply
@subsubsection @code{reply}

Define the value to be returned at the end of an @code{on} with a valued
trigger.

@example
reply ::= "reply" "(" expression ")" ";"
@end example

For example:

@example
on hello: reply (true);
@end example

@quotation Note
Reply does not mean ``return'', it merely defines the value that is
returned when the @code{on} has finished executing.  @code{reply} does
not have to be the final imperative statement, however it must occur
exactly once on every path through every sequence statements.
@end quotation

@node Return
@subsubsection @code{return}

@code{return} is used to return program execution from the body of a
function to the caller, possibly providing a value.

Implicitly returning from a @code{void} function is allowed.  Also it is
not required to use @code{return} as the last statement of a @code{void}
function, i.e., an early return skipping over remaining statements is
allowed.

@example
return ::= "return" ";"
             | "return" expression ";"
@end example

For example:

@example
void foo ()
@{
  if (idle) return;
  world;
@}

bool negate (bool b)
@{
  return !b;
@}
@end example

@node Variable
@subsubsection @code{variable}

Defining a local variable is syntactically identical to a behavior
variable:

@example
variable ::= (type identifier = expression
               | data-type identifier = data-expression
               | data-type identifier) ";"
@end example

For example:

@example
bool b = true;
bool not_idle = !idle;
bool c = negate (idle);
@end example

@node Functions
@subsection Functions

A function can is used to name and reuse a sequence of imperative
statements.

@example
function ::= type identifier "(" parameter-list ")"
               "@{" imperative-statement* "@}"
@end example

For example:

@example
void foo ()
@{
  bye;
  cruel;
  world;
@}

bool bar (bool b, int i)
@{
  if (b)
    world;
  idle = i == 12;
  return idle;
@}
@end example

Functions are allowed to be called recursively.  This includes mutual
recursive functions (function @code{f} calling function @code{g} and
vice versa).  However only as long as every function involved in the
recursion is @emph{tail recursive}; which means that a recursive call is
the last statement in the function.

@node Components
@section Components

Components are the building blocks in a Dezyne.  They allow composition
into bigger components called system components.

A component has a list of ports and optionally a behavior or a system
block.

@example
component ::= "component" "@{" port+ (behavior | system)? "@}"
behavior  ::= "behavior" "@{" behavior-statement* "@}"
system    ::= "system" "@{" system-statement* "@}"
@end example

@menu
* Ports::                       Defining a component's communication channels.
* Component Behavior::          Defining a component's behavior.
* Async Ports::                 Implementing decoupled behavior on top of sequential behavior.
* Component Types::             Three types of components.
* Component Declarative Statements::  Component-specific declarative statements.
* Component Imperative Statements::  Component-specific imperative statements.
* Multiple Provides Ports::     Providing more than one interface.
@end menu

@node Ports
@subsection Ports

@cindex port
@cindex provides
@cindex requires
A port is an instance of an interface.  A component has ports through
which it interacts with other components.  As such a port is one of the
two end-points connecting two components.

@example
port      ::= ("provides" interface-type identifier ";")
              | ("requires" qualifier? interface-type identifier ";")
qualifier ::= "external" | "injected";
@end example

The keyword @code{provides} indicates that a component implements all
of the interface behavior.

The keyword @code{requires} indicates that a component relies on some
or all of the interface behavior in its implementation.

For example:

@example
@b{provides} ihello p;
@b{requires} ihello r;
@b{requires} @b{external} itimer t;  // (1)
@b{requires} @b{injected} ilogger l; // (2)
@end example

1) port to a component with a potential delay in its communication
(@pxref{External})

2) port to a shared resource (@pxref{Systems})

Furthermore a component receives its @code{trigger}s from its
surroundings through its ports.  Note that a component @code{trigger} is
either a @code{provides-in} or a @code{requires-out} event.  If the
component emits events over its ports they are referred to as
@code{action}s.  An @code{action} is either a @code{provides-out} or a
@code{requires-in} event.

@menu
* Injection::                   Ports sharing a resource.
* External::                    Ports with external delay.
@end menu

@node Injection
@subsubsection Injection

@cindex injection
A @code{requires} port can be specified to be @code{injected}:

@example
@b{requires} @b{injected} ilogger l;
@end example

This indicates that the port can be bound to a corresponding port
residing at any level in the system hierarchy.  An @code{injected} port
is the exception to the one to one rule, i.e., it allows many ports to
be connected to a single instance.  For this reason @code{out} events
are not allowed in interfaces which are @code{injected}.

@xref{Systems} for a detailed description of the binding of injected
ports.

@node External
@subsubsection @code{external}

@cindex external
The @code{external} keyword specifies that communication over a port may
experience a delay.  This may for instance be caused by the switch
between execution contexts as in inter-process communication or the use
of threads.

@example
@b{requires} @b{external} itimer t;
@end example

During verification the delay on an @code{external} interface is
experienced an additional interleaving of events that would otherwise
not occur.

@subsubsection Race condition due to external delay

Component @code{remote_timer_proxy} illustrates how a delayed
communication channel may cause a race condition leading to illegal
behavior.

The implementation of component @code{remote_timer_proxy} is correct (no
illegal behavior) for @code{requires itimer rp} but incorrect for
@code{requires external itimer rp} due to race between @code{pp.cancel}
and @code{rp.timeout}.

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/remote-timer-proxy.dzn
@end example

@node Component Behavior
@subsection Component Behavior

The @code{behavior} section of a component defines its behavior.

@example
behavior           ::= "behavior" "@{" behavior-statement* "@}"
behavior-statement ::= type | variable | function | async-port
                         | declarative-statement
@end example

A component behavior describes the communication or the exchange of
events between a itself and other components in its environment
connected to its ports.  Each port is defined by a local name and a
behavior refers to these ports by name when it relates @code{trigger}s
and @code{action}s (see also @xref{Ports}).

@node Async Ports
@subsection Async Ports

An async port is a @code{requires} of builtin type @code{dzn.async}
which is defined in the behavior of a component.

@example
async-port      ::= "requires" "dzn.async" async-parameter-list? identifier ";"
async-parameter-list
                ::= "(" async-parameter ("," async-parameter)* ")"
async-parameter ::= data-type identifier
@end example

For example:

@example
requires dzn.async (int i) defer;
@end example

The builtin @code{dzn.async} interface can be represented like this:

@example
@verbatiminclude examples/dzn.async.dzn
@end example

@quotation Note
The use of @code{dzn.async} is discouraged for new programs, it will be
replaced by @code{defer} in version 2.16, see the ``wip-defer''
branch.
@end quotation

@node Component Types
@subsection Component Types

There are tree types of component:

@table @code
@item component, regular component, or leaf
A component that defines its implementation in its @code{behavior},
@item foreign
A component that defines only ports.  Its behavior is said to be defined
elsewhere.  This is a placeholder for a component that is implemented by
some other means, like another programming language (e.g. @code{C++}),
@item system
A component that comprises other components in its @code{system}
specification, @xref{Systems}.
@end table

@subsubsection A Leaf Component

Every component in Dezyne is a leaf component, unless it is a system
component.  The following component implements one interface and a
straightforward behavior section:

@example
@b{component} hello
@{
  @b{provides} ihello p;
  @b{requires} ihello r;
  @b{requires} itimer t;
  @b{behavior}
  @{
    @b{on} p.hello (): t.create ();
    @b{on} t.timeout (): r.hello ();
    @b{on} r.world (): p.world ();
  @}
@}
@end example

@subsubsection A Foreign Component

This component does not reveal its implementation in Dezyne under this
name.  It represents a component implemented elsewhere.  It may be
implemented in another programming language, or it is implemented in
Dezyne without exposing any of its implementation details.

@example
@b{component} timer
@{
  @b{provides} itimer t;
@}
@end example

@subsubsection A System Component

A component @code{timer_system} decomposed into two components
@code{ihello} and @code{timer} where these components are connected via
their ports.

@example
@b{component} timer_system
@{
  @b{provides} ihello p;
  @b{requires} ihello r;
  @b{system}
  @{
    hello h;
    timer t;
    p @b{<=>} h.p;
    h.t @b{<=>} t.t;
    h.r @b{<=>} r;
  @}
@}
@end example

@node Component Declarative Statements
@subsection Component Declarative Statements

For a component behavior, the list of declarative statements is extended
with @code{blocking} (@xref{Blocking}).  So we get:

@example
component-declarative-statement ::= declarative-statement | blocking
@end example

Thus, in a component, the ``declarative prefix'' includes blocking such
that the prefix consists of three elements.

@example
transition  ::= prefix imperative-statement
prefix      ::= <blocking?> <guards> <on>
@end example

@menu
* Component On::                Defining what happens on a trigger.
* Blocking::                    Implementing a synchronous call on decoupled events.
* Formal Binding::              Parameter assignment in blocking context.
* Joining Activities::          A full blocking example.
@end menu

@node Component On
@subsubsection Component @code{on}

Similar to an interface, in a component the @code{on} defines which
trigger is to be handled.  Component triggers, however, belong to
a port and carry formal parameters:

@example
on          ::= ("on" triggers ":" statement)
                  | ("on" illegal-triggers ":" illegal)
triggers    ::= trigger ("," trigger)*
trigger     ::= port-name "." event-name "(" formal-list? ")"
formal-list ::= formal ("," formal)*
formal      ::= identifier | (identifier formal-binding)
statement   ::= declarative-statement | imperative-statement | illegal
imperative-statement
            ::= action | assign | call | if | reply | return | variable
                  | imperative-compound
                  | empty-statement
illegal     ::= "illegal"
imperative-compound
            ::= "@{" (imperative-statement ";")* "@}"
empty-statement
            ::=
illegal-triggers
            ::= illegal-trigger ("," illegal-trigger)*
illegal-trigger
            ::= port-name "." event-name
@end example

The @code{formal-list} to be used is defined by the parameters of the
event definition in the interface.  Their relation is position-based.
Formal parameters may introduce another name than specified in the
@code{event} definition in the interface.

For example:

@example
on p.hello (greeting): w.hello (greeting);
on p.cruel, r.hello: illegal; // Note this is optional since 2.14.0.
@end example

When two or more imperative statements are specified for a certain
trigger, the component is said to be @emph{non-deterministic}.  For
example:

@example
on p.hello (): w.hello ();
on p.hello (): ;
@end example

non-determinism in components is not allowed and will lead to a
verification error (@xref{Verification Checks and Errors}).

The @code{formal-binding} is a feature for @code{blocking},
@xref{Formal Binding}.

@node Blocking
@subsubsection @code{blocking}

The @code{blocking} keyword is a declarative statement that can be used
in a component.

@example
blocking ::= "blocking" statement
@end example

Using @code{blocking} requires an explicit @code{reply}.  It can only be
used in a component.  If the @code{reply} is omitted for the
@code{blocking} @code{trigger}, the imperative statement of another
@code{trigger} must perform the @code{reply} for the blocked port.
Thus, time and value of a blocked port reply depend on another
@code{trigger}.  @code{blocking} may be used once in the declarative
prefix.

Only @code{provides} ports are affected by @code{blocking}.  A call of a
provides port in-event will not return before a @code{reply} is
performed for that port.

Guards or @code{on} is commutative with respect to blocking.  If
@code{blocking} appears before a guard or @code{on} it applies
to the imperative statement after the guard or @code{on}.

@quotation Note

@itemize
@item
@code{blocking} may only be used in components with a single
@code{provides} port.  This limitation may be lifted in a future
release.

@item
Systems containing @code{blocking} component instances must be
contained in a thread-safe shell (@pxref{Thread-safe Shell}).

@item
A @code{blocking} component may only appear as the top component in a
system.  This restriction will be lifted in version 2.15, or see the
``wip-blocking'' branch in git.
@end itemize
@end quotation

For example:

@example
on trigger (): blocking imperative-statement;         (1)
@end example

@example
blocking on trigger (): imperative-statement;         (2)
@end example

@example
on trigger (): blocking [guard] imperative-statement; (3)
@end example

@example
on trigger ():
@{
  blocking [guard] imperative-statement1;             (4)
  [guard] imperative-statement2;
@}
@end example

Explanation:

2) The @code{blocking} keyword applies to the
@code{imperative-statement} following @code{on trigger:}.  This form is
semantically equivalent to 1).

3) The @code{blocking} keyword applies to the @code{imperative-statement}
following @code{[guard]}.  This form is semantically equivalent to
@code{on trigger (): [guard] blocking imperative-statement;}"

4) The @code{blocking} keyword applies to @code{imperative-statement1}.
It does @emph{not} apply to @code{imperative-statement2}.

@node Formal Binding
@subsubsection Formal Binding

A formal binding @emph{binds} a member variable to an @code{out} or
@code{inout} formal parameter.  At the moment of the @code{reply}, the
value of the bound member variable is assigned to the formal parameter.

@example
trigger        ::= port-name "." event-name "(" formal-list? ")"
formal-list    ::= formal ("," formal)*
formal         ::= identifier | (identifier formal-binding)
formal-binding ::= "<-" identifier
@end example

The @code{identifier} in @code{formal-binding} must be a member variable
of the component.

For example:

@example
extern int $int$;
component blocking_binding
@{
  provides ihello h;
  requires iworld w;

  behavior
  @{
    int g = $123$;
    bool busy = false;
    [!busy] on h.hello (n <- g): blocking @{w.hello (); busy = true;@}
    [busy] on w.world (): @{g = $456$; h.reply (); busy = false;@}
    [busy] on w.cruel (): @{h.reply (); g = $456$; busy = false;@}
  @}
@}
@end example

in the case of @code{w.world} the assignment of @code{g = $456$} before
the release of the blocked thread by @code{h.reply ()} ensures that
parameter @code{n} returns with value @code{456}.  However in the case
of @code{w.cruel} the caller of @code{h.hello} receives @code{123} via
parameter @code{n}.

@quotation Note
The intent is to simplify this specific behavior in the future when data
flow verification is added.
@end quotation

@node Joining Activities
@subsubsection Joining Activities

Component @code{join} illustrates the use of @code{blocking} in
synchronizing a @code{starter} with the activities of two
@code{runner}s.

@example
